        "body": "van thibault: Been looking into the 360 camera situation again.\nThere are some problems with picking the GoPro Fusion 360:\n\n    The camera's desktop stitching software seems to not have had any updates in the last half year or so.\n    Stitching process requires gpu with atleast 4GB of ram. and 8GB of system ram. So some people might not have pc's with such specs\n    There is a CPU-only stitcher, but that takes a very long time and not sure how well maintained it is\n    Mapillary does (not advertise it much) but actually offers a way to upload your raw images from the Fusion to their servers and have it process on their end.\n    Emailed Mapillary asking some questions and they basically said that the Fusion seems abandoned by GoPro. And so they're looking into making the new GoPro Max Mapillary friendly (in regards to workflow). They'll get back to me in a couple weeks with an update on that.\n    (from what I read on the forums, the main problem is that the Max doesn't have a timelapse mode like the Fusion. And some people mentioned it doesn't center on the horizon (but I think that was someone confusing it with something else))\n    Regarding other 360 cam options, most new camera's are out of our budget range or don't offer much better quality than the GoPro' (Kandao Qoocam 8K in theory has better quality but \"early image samples don‚Äôt show much of an edge over Theta Z1, for example\")\n\nTL;DR: Waiting on Mapillary looking into the GoPro Max as potential new 'recommended 360 camera for Mapillary\n",

So some people might not have pc's with such specs\nThere is a CPU-only stitcher, but that takes a very long time and not sure how well maintained it is\nMapillary does (not advertise it much) but actually offers a way to upload your raw images from the Fusion to their servers and have it process on their end.\nEmailed Mapillary asking some questions and they basically said that the Fusion seems abandoned by GoPro. And so they're looking into making the new GoPro Max Mapillary friendly (in regards to workflow). They'll get back to me in a couple weeks with an update on that.\n(from what I read on the forums, the main problem is that the Max doesn't have a timelapse mode like the Fusion. Sinds 2008 stelt Agentschap Informatie Vlaanderen (AIV) een viewer van de 360o beeldendatabank gratis ter beschikking aan de deelnemers GDI-Vlaanderen (o.a. lokale besturen, intercommunales). De databank is vergelijkbaar met Google Streetview, maar is recenter vastgelegd, dekt een groter gebied (inclusief kleine wegen, doodlopende straten) en heeft een betere resolutie en technologie die zorgt voor een grotere nauwkeurigheid van metingen.\n\nDe beelden in de databank zijn echter verouderd (2012-2014) en zijn aan vervanging toe. Het is bijgevolg noodzakelijk om een nieuwe beeldendatabank te laten cre√´ren.\n\nDe 360o beeldendatabank wordt binnen Fluvius dagelijks gebruikt om een eerste zicht te krijgen op een terreinsituatie bij diverse vragen, klachten van derden, het voorbereiden van een co√∂rdinatievergadering, ondersteunend te zijn bij ontwerpen (kleine werken en aansluitingswerken worden op basis van deze beelden ontworpen zonder verplaatsing) en opmaken van vergunningsaanvragen.\n\nDaarnaast biedt het de mogelijkheid de migratie van geografische gegevens en inventarisatie van de openbare verlichting, luchtnet en bovengrondse assets te faciliteren alsook de datakwaliteit te verbeteren.\n\nDe beelden hebben ook nog potentieel (eventueel in combinatie met beeldherkenningsalgoritmes) in toepassingsgebieden dewelke op heden nog niet gebruikt worden bij Fluvius, zoals onder meer:\n\n‚Äî Line of sight based producten (plaatsing sensoren, wifi, 5G),\n\n‚Äî gebruik bij 3D ontwerpen van bovengrondse infrastructuur en as-built liggingsplannen,\n\n‚Äî bepalen van de asset health (loodrechtheid van palen, laaghangende bovengrondse leidingen, [...]),\n\n‚Äî conditie beoordeling wegenis.",

Ik kijk enkel naar Samsung, aangezien zij de enige echte betrouwbare zijn in ogen. Andere firma's liegen soms in hun specificaties)\n\nAndere oplossing is een gewone HDD. Er zijn rugged casen, maar het is waarschijnlijk beter om een normale encslure te steken in een soort van foam doos.\n- **PLUS** Goedkoper (16TB Seagate Exos (maar ben nog niet zeker of die goed is voor zoveel vibraties met shipping enz) kost 285 euro.)\n- **MIN** Meer kans op dataverlies door schijf die kaputsch gaat. Zeker als het zo vaak heen en weer geshipped wordt. The processing chain is awkward with a custom geotag program so I haven‚Äôt bothered to document the workflow. The advantage over photo timelapse is that the GoPro app can do horizon leveling.<br><a href=\"https://forum.mapillary.com/t/gopro-max-time-lapse-interval-and-location-exif/5309/18\">https://forum.mapillary.com/t/gopro-max-time-lapse-interval-and-location-exif/5309/18</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n",

    {
      "content": {
        "body": "So - just so you don't make this mistake - I've almost lost 58km of streetview work yesterday. As I was running out of space for backing up my images, I had decided to leave the previous day's 360 images on the microSD card and not reformat it, so I would have a copy on my hard drive and one on the card. That was a critical mistake. The Mapillary uploader uploaded log files and possibly modified some of the images on the SD card, messing up the file system. When I used the SD card and the camera yesterday, everything looked normal. The card was detected, the camera was recording timelapses as usual, and I rode my bike for 58 km across Woluwe - but when I got home, I realised the GoPro couldn't preview the images I took. When I looked at the SD card, only the previous day's images were displayed in the Finder/File Explorer. Yet the SD card was showing as almost full, so I suspected the data had been stored (even if not listed as files). Fortunately I had previously purchased a data recovery software (Disk Drill) which allowed me to recover about 80% of the images directly, and another 10% after a deeper scan. So 6714 images were saved from yesterday's mission, not as many as I wanted (probably lost 600) but at least I didn't lose a full day of my life cycling on my Brompton in circles around the fancy houses of Woluwe for nothing. \n\nTL;DR: almost lost a full day of work because Mapillary uploaded corrupted the file system of my SD card. Always reformat the card before going out !",
        "msgtype": "m.text",
        "org.matrix.msc1767.text": "So - just so you don't make this mistake - I've almost lost 58km of streetview work yesterday. As I was running out of space for backing up my images, I had decided to leave the previous day's 360 images on the microSD card and not reformat it, so I would have a copy on my hard drive and one on the card. That was a critical mistake. The Mapillary uploader uploaded log files and possibly modified some of the images on the SD card, messing up the file system. When I used the SD card and the camera yesterday, everything looked normal. The card was detected, the camera was recording timelapses as usual, and I rode my bike for 58 km across Woluwe - but when I got home, I realised the GoPro couldn't preview the images I took. When I looked at the SD card, only the previous day's images were displayed in the Finder/File Explorer. Yet the SD card was showing as almost full, so I suspected the data had been stored (even if not listed as files). Fortunately I had previously purchased a data recovery software (Disk Drill) which allowed me to recover about 80% of the images directly, and another 10% after a deeper scan. So 6714 images were saved from yesterday's mission, not as many as I wanted (probably lost 600) but at least I didn't lose a full day of my life cycling on my Brompton in circles around the fancy houses of Woluwe for nothing. \n\nTL;DR: almost lost a full day of work because Mapillary uploaded corrupted the file system of my SD card. Always reformat the card before going out !"

I don't need to see my toes or my nose, but I do want to see what's on the ground in front of me. So I used a 20 cm gooseneck between the helmet mount and the camera. This also allowed me to position the camera exacty over the middle of the helmet when wearing it. I needed someone else to fix the position from all directions while I had the helmet on and held my head straight. And I used two very tight tiewraps so the mount couldn't get loose.         "body": "Thibaultmol: \n1) the screen of the camera should face to the back. Be aware: the camera can also switch orientation, as Joost explained just before. The short manual points this out\n2) You can turn the plastic piece either way. By putting it in the one or the other position, you can usually compensate a little bit if vent holes (and thus the straps) are a bit too much to the front or to the back of your hands\n3) I did it like you did, but I also wished they would stay a bit more firmly attached.       "content": {
        "body": "> <@Seppe:matrix.org> Using the helmet for walking has the disadvantage that you kinda have to keep your head straight (in 3 axes) the whole time. If you have a good backpack setup, you can at least turn your head around as much as you like.\n\nThat's what I thought in advance... turned out that the head keeps itself reasonably straight all the time, while the backpack swings, tilts and sways with all body movements. The only thing your head does more than your back, is turning around the vertical axis. When crossing a road you have to turn your head multiple times. But in the resulting photo sequence that is not really a problem! \n1. You have 360 all around anyway, \n2. Most of the head turns are outside the timed snapshots, \n3. It's not a problem to have intermediate photos looking to the sides when there is actually something to see, such as a crossing road with mappable elements such as street signs, markings, kerbs, hedges, traffic calming features, crossing islands, buildings/natural/landuse.",

        "body": "I could be wrong, but i'm pretty sure that gopro player will cut the video but has to reencode the entire video. which means that another layer of recompression will happen. What I remember doing many years ago was using the command line tool ffmpeg (the most popular video command line tool) to cut the video. \nThe resulting video is technically going to be corrupt in the first second or so because it got cut where it was expecting a keyframe (video encoding basically does a keyframe every so many frames and then just delta frames to tell what's different from the original keyframe. if it has delta frames but not the original keyframe, it won't be able to do  that first second BUT the rest of the video stays untouched)",

    {
      "content": {
        "body": "kvde I haven't ran this script. But GPT4 tried to make one based on the readme, maybe this helps you get started atleast?\n\n\n```python\n# Import required modules\nfrom libs.tools import *\nfrom libs.graph_route import plot_graph_route\nimport networkx as nx\nimport osmnx as ox\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nfrom network import Network\nfrom network.algorithms import hierholzer\n\n# Custom filter and location definition\nCUSTOM_FILTER = (\n    '[\"highway\"][\"area\"!~\"yes\"][\"highway\"!~\"bridleway|bus_guideway|bus_stop|construction|'\n    'cycleway|elevator|footway|motorway|motorway_junction|motorway_link|escalator|proposed|'\n    'construction|platform|raceway|rest_area|path|service\"][\"access\"!~\"customers|no|private\"]'\n    '[\"public_transport\"!~\"platform\"][\"fee\"!~\"yes\"][\"foot\"!~\"no\"][\"service\"!~\"drive-through|'\n    'driveway|parking_aisle\"][\"toll\"!~\"yes\"]'\n)\nlocation = \"The Grange, Edinburgh, Scotland\"\n\n# Get the graph from OSMnx\norg_graph = ox.graph_from_place(location, custom_filter=CUSTOM_FILTER)\n\n# Simplify the graph to undirected\ngraph = ox.utils_graph.get_undirected(org_graph)\n\n# Find odd degree nodes and calculate shortest distance\nodd_degree_nodes = get_odd_degree_nodes(graph)\npair_weights = get_shortest_distance_for_odd_degrees(graph, odd_degree_nodes)\nmatched_edges_with_weights = min_matching(pair_weights)\n\n# Plot graph with minimal matching\nfig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 8), facecolor='black', frameon=False)\nfor v, u, w in matched_edges_with_weights:\n    x = graph.nodes[v][\"x\"], graph.nodes[u][\"x\"]\n    y = graph.nodes[v][\"y\"], graph.nodes[u][\"y\"]\n    ax.plot(x, y, c='red', alpha=0.3)\n    ax.scatter(x, y, c='red', edgecolor=\"none\")\n\n# Plot the graph\nfig, ax = ox.plot_graph(graph, node_zorder=2, node_color='g', bgcolor='k', ax=ax)\n\n# List edges and find the Eulerian path\nsingle_edges = [(u, v) for u, v, k in graph.edges]\nadded_edges = get_shortest_paths(graph, matched_edges_with_weights)\nedges = map_osmnx_edges2integers(graph, single_edges + added_edges)\n\n# Find the Eulerian path\nnetwork = Network(len(graph.nodes), edges, weighted=True)\neulerian_path = hierholzer(network)\n\n# Find final path\nconverted_eulerian_path = convert_integer_path2osmnx_nodes(eulerian_path, graph.nodes())\ndouble_edge_heap = get_double_edge_heap(org_graph)\nfinal_path = convert_path(graph, converted_eulerian_path, double_edge_heap)\n\n# Plot graph route\nfig, ax = plot_graph_route(org_graph, final_path, route_linewidth=6, node_size=0, bgcolor=\"w\", route_alpha=0.2, route_color=\"w\")\n\n# Save images for GIF\nfor i, e in enumerate(final_path, start=1):\n    fig, ax = plot_graph_route(org_graph, final_path[:i], route_linewidth=6, node_size=0, bgcolor=\"w\", route_alpha=0.2)\n    ax.set_title(location)\n    fig.savefig(f\"/img_{i}.png\", dpi=120, bbox_inches=\"tight\")\n```\n\n> Please note that this script assumes you have the necessary `libs` and `network` modules available in your environment, as well as the necessary packages like osmnx, networkx, and matplotlib installed. The script also assumes you have the correct directory structure for saving the images for the GIF. If not, you'll need to adjust the directory path accordingly in the fig.savefig(f\"/img\\_{i}.png\", dpi=120, bbox\\_inches=\"tight\") line.\n> \n> Also, it's worth noting that if you are running this script in a local environment, you might need to adjust the settings or install additional dependencies, depending on your specific environment setup.\n> \n> If you encounter any errors, they're likely due to a missing package or an improperly referenced module, and you'll need to debug accordingly.\n> \n> This script is a basic one and doesn't handle exceptions. get_odd_degree_nodes(graph)\npair_weights = get_shortest_distance_for_odd_degrees(graph, odd_degree_nodes)\nmatched_edges_with_weights = min_matching(pair_weights)\n\n# Plot graph with minimal matching\nfig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 8), facecolor='black', frameon=False)\nfor v, u, w in matched_edges_with_weights:\n    x = graph.nodes[v][&quot;x&quot;], graph.nodes[u][&quot;x&quot;]\n get_shortest_paths(graph, matched_edges_with_weights)\nedges = map_osmnx_edges2integers(graph, single_edges + added_edges)\n\n# Find the Eulerian path\nnetwork = Network(len(graph.nodes), edges, weighted=True)\neulerian_path = hierholzer(network)\n\n# Find final path\nconverted_eulerian_path = convert_integer_path2osmnx_nodes(eulerian_path, graph.nodes())\ndouble_edge_heap = get_double_edge_heap(org_graph)\nfinal_path = convert_path(graph, converted_eulerian_path, double_edge_heap)\n\n# Plot graph route\nfig, ax = plot_graph_route(org_graph, final_path, route_linewidth=6, node_size=0, bgcolor=&quot;w&quot;, route_alpha=0.2, route_color=&quot;w&quot;)\n\n# Save images for GIF\nfor i, e in enumerate(final_path, start=1):\n    fig, ax = plot_graph_route(org_graph, final_path[:i], route_linewidth=6, node_size=0, bgcolor=&quot;w&quot;, route_alpha=0.2)\n    ax.set_title(location)\n    fig.savefig(f&quot;/img_{i}.png&quot;, dpi=120, bbox_inches=&quot;tight&quot;)\n</code></pre>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Please note that this script assumes you have the necessary <code>libs</code> and <code>network</code> modules available in your definition\nCUSTOM_FILTER = (\n    '[\"highway\"][\"area\"!~\"yes\"][\"highway\"!~\"bridleway|bus_guideway|bus_stop|construction|'\n    'cycleway|elevator|footway|motorway|motorway_junction|motorway_link|escalator|proposed|'\n    'construction|platform|raceway|rest_area|path|service\"][\"access\"!~\"customers|no|private\"]'\n get_shortest_distance_for_odd_degrees(graph, odd_degree_nodes)\nmatched_edges_with_weights = min_matching(pair_weights)\n\n# Plot graph with minimal matching\nfig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 8), facecolor='black', frameon=False)\nfor v, u, w in matched_edges_with_weights:\n    x = graph.nodes[v][\"x\"], graph.nodes[u][\"x\"]\n    y = graph.nodes[v][\"y\"], graph.nodes[u][\"y\"]\n    ax.plot(x, y, c='red', alpha=0.3)\n    ax.scatter(x, y, c='red', edgecolor=\"none\")\n\n# Plot the graph\nfig, ax = ox.plot_graph(graph, node_zorder=2, node_color='g', bgcolor='k', ax=ax)\n\n# List edges and find the Eulerian path\nsingle_edges = [(u, v) for u, v, k in graph.edges]\nadded_edges = get_shortest_paths(graph, matched_edges_with_weights)\nedges = map_osmnx_edges2integers(graph, single_edges + added_edges)\n\n# Find the Eulerian path\nnetwork = Network(len(graph.nodes), edges, weighted=True)\neulerian_path = hierholzer(network)\n\n# Find final path\nconverted_eulerian_path = convert_integer_path2osmnx_nodes(eulerian_path, graph.nodes())\ndouble_edge_heap = get_double_edge_heap(org_graph)\nfinal_path = convert_path(graph, converted_eulerian_path, double_edge_heap)\n\n# Plot graph route\nfig, ax = plot_graph_route(org_graph, final_path, route_linewidth=6, node_size=0, bgcolor=\"w\", route_alpha=0.2, route_color=\"w\")\n\n# Save images for GIF\nfor i, e in enumerate(final_path, start=1):\n    fig, ax = plot_graph_route(org_graph, final_path[:i], route_linewidth=6, node_size=0, bgcolor=\"w\", route_alpha=0.2)\n    ax.set_title(location)\n    fig.savefig(f\"/img_{i}.png\", dpi=120, bbox_inches=\"tight\")\n```\n\n> Please note that this script assumes you have the necessary `libs` and `network` modules available in your environment, as well weighted=True)\neulerian_path = hierholzer(network)\n\n# Find final path\nconverted_eulerian_path = convert_integer_path2osmnx_nodes(eulerian_path, graph.nodes())\ndouble_edge_heap = get_double_edge_heap(org_graph)\nfinal_path = convert_path(graph, converted_eulerian_path, double_edge_heap)\n\n# Plot graph route\nfig, ax = plot_graph_route(org_graph, final_path, route_linewidth=6, node_size=0, bgcolor=&quot;w&quot;, route_alpha=0.2, route_color=&quot;w&quot;)\n\n# Save images for GIF\nfor i, e in enumerate(final_path, start=1):\n    fig, ax = plot_graph_route(org_graph,     {
      "content": {
        "body": "I actually talked about this during my talk. Initially I was going for a neighbourhood approach: taking every turn at every street, to ensure I don't forget anything in a very small area. But then I realised I was passing many times in the same streets, again and again, wasting time and energy, so I changed to a long-game aproach, going from one end of a street all the way to the end, in a E-W-E-W pattern, then doing the N-S-N-S another time. Pros: less turns, easier to follow directions, better GPS accuracy, and easier to watch a sequence on Mapillary. Cons: you need to better plan and come back only after a few days to ensure you didn't miss any side street.",

    {
      "content": {
        "body": "Re the \"goals\" hans.vandenabeele: some of it is explained here https://openstreetmap.be/nl/projects/streetlevelimagery.html\nWith this project, just having a Google Street view alternative that's actually open data is a goal in itself. For most of us here, the use for osm is obviously important. In practice, most of that is just \"I'm mapping something somewhere, and I want to look at the images to help digitize stuff\". So 360 is excellent, even in lower resolution, because you get an idea of the area very quickly. The higher the resolution, the better of course, because them you can read housenumbers, details of traffic signs, shop names etc.\nThe AI part currently happens purely on Mapillary end, and it generates useful data. For example georeferenced stuff like benches, road lay out, traffic signs,...\nIf we could do the ai part on our end, that'd be awesome. I see that as an extension of the GeoVisio program though. Also note that we already have more data than our mappers can process, so generating a million benches doesn't really help all that much. The challenge is finding the smallest number of detections with the biggest impact. Or creating flows that can help you work real fast\n",
        "format": "org.matrix.custom.html",
        "formatted_body": "Re the \"goals\" <a href=\"https://matrix.to/#/@hans.vandenabeele:matrix.org\">hans.vandenabeele</a>: some of it is explained here https://openstreetmap.be/nl/projects/streetlevelimagery.html\nWith this project, just having a Google Street view alternative that's actually open data is a goal in itself. For most of us here, the use for osm is obviously important. In practice, most of that is just \"I'm mapping something somewhere, and I want to look at the images to help digitize stuff\". So 360 is excellent, even in lower resolution, because you get an idea of the area very quickly. The higher the resolution, the better of course, because them you can read housenumbers, details of traffic signs, shop names etc.\nThe AI part currently happens purely on Mapillary end, and it generates useful data. For example georeferenced stuff like benches, road lay out, traffic signs,...\nIf we could do the ai part on our end, that'd be awesome. I see that as an extension of the GeoVisio program though. Also note that we already have more data than our mappers can process, so generating a million benches doesn't really help all that much. The challenge is finding the smallest number of detections with the biggest impact. Or creating flows that can help you work real fast\n",

      "content": {
        "body": "Thanks Joost! I consider these camera+GPS data as something for \"edge computing\". As I understand OSM/Mapillary/... currently, that's to centralise everything. I've been filling TB disks since years, to the extend my (pocket)money for storage and computing power (own servers) ran out. Since, I scale down photos/videos and use dockers to split the types of processing to be able to scale up on (older) desktops that hang around here (cutting all overhead like virus scans, using just minimal ubuntu etc) to extract the real information from all data that photos/videos are. After extraction, say augmenting the footage (like PDF \"scan img\" + OCR text overlay), then I replace the original files (overwrite) with the enriched version. Depending on the application, it could mean a much smaller MP4 (lower resolution at least, typically downsampled 1:2 or 1:3 so that the files become 4-9 times smaller) with a .srt/vtt/... file joining the file. Offloading such processing allows parallel processing and could reduce the current delays sequences face. Does this trigger bells?",

        "body": "keep in mind: a 360 image is just stored as a 2d image. So resolution is high in the center but low in the poles. If you rotate that, you're moving high res regions to low res regions and the opposite. So it's much worse than rotating a 2d image\n\n> As you move towards the poles of the 360-degree image, the resolution decreases because the same number of pixels now represents a smaller area of the scene. When rotating a 360-degree image, the interpolation process has to deal not only with the typical challenges of rotating a standard image but also with the varying resolution across different parts of the 360-degree image. This can lead to more pronounced quality degradation, especially in the areas where the resolution is initially lower.",
        "format": "org.matrix.custom.html",
        "formatted_body": "<p>keep in mind: a 360 image is just stored as a 2d image. So resolution is high in the center but low in the poles. If you rotate that, you're moving high res regions to low res regions and the opposite. So it's much worse than rotating a 2d image</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>As you move towards the poles of the 360-degree image, the resolution decreases because the same number of pixels now represents a smaller area of the scene. When rotating a 360-degree image, the interpolation process has to deal not only with the typical challenges of rotating a standard image but also with the varying resolution across different parts of the 360-degree image. This can lead to more pronounced quality degradation, especially in the areas where the resolution is initially lower.</p>\n</blockquote>\n",
